🧵 1️⃣ What Is a Virtual Thread?

First understand the old model

🟠 Before (Java 8, 11, 17)

If you create:

new Thread(() -> doWork()).start();

That thread is:

👉 Mapped 1-to-1 with an OS thread

Meaning:

1 Java thread = 1 Operating System thread

Problems:

-OS threads are heavy
-Limited (few thousands max)
-Large stack memory (1MB per thread default)
-Context switching is expensive

So if you create 100,000 threads → 💥 system crash or huge memory usage.

🔵 Now: Virtual Threads (Java 21+, available in Java 25)

Virtual Threads come from Project Loom.

Now:

Many Java threads  →  Few OS threads

Instead of:

1 Java thread = 1 OS thread

We have:

100,000 virtual threads
       ↓
Scheduled on maybe 8–16 real OS threads


🧠 What does that mean?

Virtual threads are:

a.Very lightweight
b.Created in huge numbers
c.Managed by the JVM, not the OS
d.Parked and resumed efficiently


📦 How are they different internally?

Platform Thread (old):

(i)    Has its own OS stack
(ii)   Heavy
(iii)  OS does scheduling
(iv)   Virtual Thread
(v)    Stack stored in heap
(vi)   JVM scheduler manages it
(vii)  When blocked (like I/O), it is unmounted
(viii) OS thread is freed for other work


🧠 Simple Analogy

Old model:

Each customer gets a dedicated waiter.

Virtual thread model:

Few waiters serve many customers efficiently.

🎯 Why This Matters for GC

Since virtual thread stacks are stored in heap:

-They are visible to GC
-More scalable
-Better memory usage
-Less pressure compared to thousands of OS stacks